About the dataset

The data set consists of 3 folders, i.e., 'test', 'train', and 'validation'. Each of these folders has four subfolders:

happy: Images of people who have happy facial expressions.
sad: Images of people with sad or upset facial expressions.
surprise: Images of people who have shocked or surprised facial expressions.
neutral: Images of people showing no prominent emotion in their facial expression at all.

Checking Distribution of Classes

In[]:
base_path = 'python_data_science/Facial_emotion_images/'
emotions = ['happy', 'sad', 'surprise', 'neutral']
splits = ['train', 'validation', 'test']

# Dictionary to store all counts
all_counts = {}
split_totals = {}
grand_total = 0

# Gathering all the data
for split in splits:
    split_path = os.path.join(base_path, split)
    split_total = 0
    all_counts[split] = {}

    for emotion in emotions:
        emotion_path = os.path.join(split_path, emotion)
        if os.path.exists(emotion_path):
            count = len(os.listdir(emotion_path))
            all_counts[split][emotion] = count
            split_total += count
        else:
            all_counts[split][emotion] = 0

    split_totals[split] = split_total
    grand_total += split_total

# Displaying class distribution for all classes
for split in splits:
    print(f"\n{split.upper()} SET:")
    print("-" * 40)

    split_total = split_totals[split]

    for emotion in emotions:
        count = all_counts[split][emotion]
        if split_total > 0:
            percentage = (count / split_total) * 100
            print(f"{emotion.capitalize()}: {count} images ({percentage:.1f}%)")
        else:
            print(f"{emotion.capitalize()}: {count} images")

    print(f"{'Total'}: {split_total} images")

# Percentage of data split between train,test and validation
print("-" * 40)
print(f"\nTotal dataset size: {grand_total} images")
print(f"\nData split percentages:")

for split in splits:
    split_total = split_totals[split]
    if grand_total > 0:
        split_percentage = (split_total / grand_total) * 100
        print(f"{split.capitalize()}: {split_total} images ({split_percentage:.1f}%)")
    else:
        print(f"{split.capitalize()}: {split_total} images")

Creating the Base Neural Network

In[]:
# Creating the base CNN model
def create_base_cnn(input_shape=(48, 48, 1), num_classes=4):
    model = Sequential([
        # Preprocessing layer and normalizing to [0,1]
        Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=input_shape),

        # First Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool1'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout1'),

        # Second Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool2'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout2'),

        # Third Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv3'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool3'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout3'),

        # Flatten and Dense layers
        Flatten(name='flatten'),
        Dense(512, activation='relu', name='dense1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn_dense'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout_dense'),

        # Output layer
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='output')
    ])

    return model

# Createing and compiling the model
base_cnn = create_base_cnn(input_shape=(48, 48, 1), num_classes=4)

# Displaying model architecture
base_cnn.summary()

Compiling and Training the Model with Grayscale data loader

In[]:
# Compiling the model
base_cnn.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# Training parameters
EPOCHS = 20

# Defining callbacks for better training
callbacks = [
    tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_accuracy',
        patience=5,
        restore_best_weights=True,
        verbose=1
    ),
    tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,
        patience=3,
        min_lr=1e-7,
        verbose=1
    )
]

# Training the model using grayscale data loader
history = base_cnn.fit(
    train_ds_gray,
    validation_data=validation_ds_gray,
    epochs=EPOCHS,
    callbacks=callbacks,
    verbose=1
)


# Plotting training history
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5))

# Creating the base CNN model for RGB images (48x48x3)
def create_base_cnn_rgb(input_shape=(48, 48, 3), num_classes=4):
    model = Sequential([
        # Preprocessing layer (normalize to [0,1])
        Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=input_shape),

        # First Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool1'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout1'),

        # Second Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool2'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout2'),

        # Third Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv3'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool3'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout3'),

        # Flatten and Dense layers
        Flatten(name='flatten'),
        Dense(512, activation='relu', name='dense1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn_dense'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout_dense'),

        # Output layer
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='output')
    ])

    return model

# Create and compile the RGB model
base_cnn_rgb = create_base_cnn_rgb(input_shape=(48, 48, 3), num_classes=4)

# Compile the model
base_cnn_rgb.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# Display model architecture
print("BASE CNN FOR RGB IMAGES")
print("="*50)
base_cnn_rgb.summary()

# creating second CNN model with larger architecture
def create_second_cnn(input_shape=(48, 48, 1), num_classes=4):
    model = Sequential([
        # Preprocessing layer and normalizing to [0,1]
        Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=input_shape),

        # First Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1'),
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv1_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool1'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout1'),

        # Second Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2'),
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv2_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool2'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout2'),

        # Third Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv3'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3'),
        Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv3_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool3'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout3'),

        # Fourth Convolutional Block (Additional layer)
        Conv2D(512, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', name='conv4'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn4'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool4'),
        Dropout(0.3, name='dropout4'),

        # Flatten and Dense layers
        Flatten(name='flatten'),
        Dense(1024, activation='relu', name='dense1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn_dense1'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout_dense1'),

        Dense(512, activation='relu', name='dense2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn_dense2'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout_dense2'),

        # Output layer
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='output')
    ])

    return model

# Creating and compiling the second model

Creating the second Convolutional Neural Network for RGB Data loader

In[]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import (
    Rescaling, Conv2D, BatchNormalization, MaxPooling2D,
    Dropout, GlobalAveragePooling2D, Dense
)
from tensorflow.keras.regularizers import l2

# Creating second CNN model for RGB data with reduced overfitting
def create_second_cnn_rgb(input_shape=(48, 48, 3), num_classes=4):
    model = Sequential([
        # Preprocessing layer (normalize to [0,1])
        Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=input_shape),

        # First Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1'),
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv1_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool1'),
        Dropout(0.3, name='dropout1'),

        # Second Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2'),
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv2_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool2'),
        Dropout(0.35, name='dropout2'),

        # Third Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv3'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3'),
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv3_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool3'),
        Dropout(0.4, name='dropout3'),

        # Fourth Convolutional Block (reduced filters)
        Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='conv4'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn4'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool4'),
        Dropout(0.45, name='dropout4'),

        # Use GAP instead of Flatten to drastically cut parameters
        GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='gap'),

        # Dense layers with L2 and Dropout
        Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4), name='dense1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn_dense1'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout_dense1'),

        # Output layer
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='output')
    ])

    return model


# Creating and compiling the reduced-overfitting CNN model
second_cnn_rgb = create_second_cnn_rgb(input_shape=(48, 48, 3), num_classes=4)

print("SECOND CNN - RGB VERSION")
print("="*50)
second_cnn_rgb.summary()

# Count parameters
total_params = second_cnn_rgb.count_params()
trainable_params = sum([tf.keras.backend.count_params(w) for w in second_cnn_rgb.trainable_weights])
non_trainable_params = total_params - trainable_params
print("\nMODEL PARAMETERS:")
print(f"Total parameters: {total_params:,}")
print(f"Trainable parameters: {trainable_params:,}")
print(f"Non-trainable parameters: {non_trainable_params:,}")
print("\nSecond CNN RGB model created successfully!")

Transfer Learning Architectures

In this section, we will create several Transfer Learning architectures. For the pre-trained models, we will select three popular architectures namely, VGG16, ResNet v2, and Efficient Net. The difference between these architectures and the previous architectures is that these will require 3 input channels while the earlier ones worked on 'grayscale' images. Therefore, we need to create new DataLoaders.

Creating our Data Loaders for Transfer Learning Architectures

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network. We will have to go with color_mode = 'rgb' as this is the required format for the transfer learning architectures.

In[]:

# Performance optimization
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.AUTOTUNE

def optimize_dataset(dataset):
    """Optimizing dataset for better performance"""
    return dataset.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

# Optimizing RGB datasets for transfer learning
train_ds_rgb = optimize_dataset(train_ds_rgb)
validation_ds_rgb = optimize_dataset(validation_ds_rgb)
test_ds_rgb = optimize_dataset(test_ds_rgb)

print("All RGB datasets optimized for performance!")

# Preprocessing for different transfer learning models
def preprocess_for_vgg(image, label):
    """Preprocessing images for VGG16 models"""
    # VGG expects inputs in range [0, 255] but with specific preprocessing
    from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import preprocess_input
    return preprocess_input(image), label

def preprocess_for_resnet(image, label):
    """Preprocessing images for ResNet models"""
    from tensorflow.keras.applications.resnet_v2 import preprocess_input
    return preprocess_input(image), label

def preprocess_for_efficientnet(image, label):
    """Preprocessing images for EfficientNet models"""
    from tensorflow.keras.applications.efficientnet import preprocess_input
    return preprocess_input(image), label

# Creating preprocessed datasets for different architectures
print("\nCreating model-specific preprocessed datasets...")

# For VGG16
train_ds_vgg = train_ds_rgb.map(preprocess_for_vgg, num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)
validation_ds_vgg = validation_ds_rgb.map(preprocess_for_vgg, num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)
test_ds_vgg = test_ds_rgb.map(preprocess_for_vgg, num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)

test_ds_resnet = test_ds_rgb.map(preprocess_for_resnet, num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)

# For EfficientNet

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16

Model Building

  • Import VGG16 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In[]:
# Creating VGG16 model for facial emotion detection
def create_vgg16_emotion_model(num_classes=4):
    # Import VGG16 base model (pre-trained on ImageNet)
    vgg16_base = VGG16(
        weights='imagenet',
        include_top=False,
        input_shape=(224, 224, 3),
        pooling=None
    )

    # Freezing the base model layers
    vgg16_base.trainable = False

    # Building the complete model
    model = Sequential([
        # VGG16 base model
        vgg16_base,

        # Global Average Pooling
        GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_avg_pool'),

        # Custom fully connected layers
        Dense(1024, activation='relu', name='fc1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout1'),

        Dense(512, activation='relu', name='fc2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout2'),

        Dense(256, activation='relu', name='fc3'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3'),
        Dropout(0.3, name='dropout3'),

        # Output layer for 4 emotions
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='predictions')
    ])

    return model

# Creating the VGG16 model
print("Creating VGG16 Model for Facial Emotion Detection...")
print("="*60)

vgg16_model = create_vgg16_emotion_model(num_classes=4)

# Compiling the model
vgg16_model.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.0001),
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# Displaying model architecture
print("\nVGG16 Model Architecture:")
vgg16_model.summary()

print("VGG16 model created and compiled successfully!")

from tensorflow.keras.applications import ResNet50V2

Model Building

In[]:
# Creating ResNet V2 model for facial emotion detection
def create_resnet_v2_emotion_model(num_classes=4):
    # Import ResNet50V2 base model (pre-trained on ImageNet)
    resnet_base = ResNet50V2(
        weights='imagenet',
        include_top=False,
        input_shape=(224, 224, 3),
        pooling=None
    )

    # Freezing the base model layers
    resnet_base.trainable = False

    # Building the complete model
    model = Sequential([
        # ResNet V2 base model
        resnet_base,

        # Global Average Pooling
        GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_avg_pool'),

        # Custom fully connected layers
        Dense(1024, activation='relu', name='fc1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout1'),

        Dense(512, activation='relu', name='fc2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout2'),

        Dense(256, activation='relu', name='fc3'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3'),
        Dropout(0.3, name='dropout3'),

        # Output layer for 4 emotions
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='predictions')
    ])

    return model

# Creating the ResNet V2 model
print("Creating ResNet V2 Model for Facial Emotion Detection...")
print("="*60)

resnet_model = create_resnet_v2_emotion_model(num_classes=4)


# Displaying model architecture
print("\nResNet V2 Model Architecture:")
resnet_model.summary()

print("ResNet V2 model created successfully!")

callbacks = [
    tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        'best_resnet_model.h5',
        monitor='val_accuracy',
        save_best_only=True,
        save_weights_only=False,
        verbose=1
    ),
    tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_accuracy',
        patience=7,
        restore_best_weights=True,
        verbose=1
    ),
    tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,
        patience=4,
        min_lr=1e-7,
        verbose=1
    )
]

# Creating EfficientNet Model for Facial Emotion Detection
def create_efficientnet_emotion_model(num_classes=4, dropout_rate=0.4):
    # Importing EfficientNetB0 base model (pretrained on ImageNet)
    efficientnet_base = EfficientNetB0(
        weights='imagenet',
        include_top=False,
        input_shape=(224, 224, 3)
    )

    # Freezing the base model layers for initial training phase
    efficientnet_base.trainable = False

    # Model architecture (lighter head than before for better generalization)
    inputs = tf.keras.Input(shape=(224, 224, 3))

    # Preprocessing inside the model to match EfficientNet training requirements
    x = tf.keras.applications.efficientnet.preprocess_input(inputs)

    # Pass through base model in inference mode while frozen
    x = efficientnet_base(x, training=False)

    # Global average pooling to reduce spatial dimensions
    x = GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_avg_pool')(x)

    # Fully connected head
    x = Dense(256, activation='relu', name='fc')(x)
    x = Dropout(dropout_rate, name='dropout')(x)

    # Output layer for emotion classes
    outputs = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='predictions')(x)

    # Final model
    model = Model(inputs, outputs, name="EfficientNetB0_Emotion")
    return model, efficientnet_base


# Helper function to unfreeze top blocks for fine-tuning
def unfreeze_top_blocks(base_model, blocks=('block6', 'block7'), freeze_batchnorm=True):
    base_model.trainable = True
    for layer in base_model.layers:
        # Only unfreeze layers from specified top blocks
        train_this = any(b in layer.name for b in blocks)
        layer.trainable = train_this
        # Keep BatchNorm frozen to prevent statistics drift
        if freeze_batchnorm and isinstance(layer, tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization):
            layer.trainable = False


# Create the model
print("Creating EfficientNet Model for Facial Emotion Detection...")
print("="*60)
efficientnet_model, base_model = create_efficientnet_emotion_model(num_classes=4, dropout_rate=0.4)

# Display model architecture
print("\nEfficientNet Model Architecture:")
efficientnet_model.summary()
print("EfficientNet model created successfully!")

Building a Complex Neural Network Architecture

In this section, we will build a more complex Convolutional Neural Network Model that has close to as many parameters as we had in our Transfer Learning Models. However, we will have only 1 input channel for our input images.

Creating our Data Loaders

In this section, we are creating data loaders which we will use as inputs to the more Complicated Convolutional Neural Network. We will go ahead with color_mode = 'grayscale'.

from tensorflow.keras.regularizers import l2

# Creating a complex CNN model with 5 Convolutional Blocks (reduced overfitting)
def create_complex_cnn(input_shape=(48, 48, 1), num_classes=4, weight_decay=1e-4):
    model = Sequential([
        # Preprocessing layer and normalize to [0,1]
        Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=input_shape),

        # First Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv1_1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1_1'),
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv1_2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn1_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool1'),
        Dropout(0.25, name='dropout1'),

        # Second Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv2_1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2_1'),
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv2_2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn2_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool2'),
        Dropout(0.3, name='dropout2'),

        # Third Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv3_1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3_1'),
        Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv3_2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn3_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool3'),
        Dropout(0.35, name='dropout3'),

        # Fourth Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(192, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv4_1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn4_1'),
        Conv2D(192, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv4_2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn4_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool4'),
        Dropout(0.4, name='dropout4'),

        # Fifth Convolutional Block
        Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv5_1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn5_1'),
        Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='conv5_2'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn5_2'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2), name='pool5'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout5'),

        # Global Average Pooling
        GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_avg_pool'),

        # Dense head
        Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(weight_decay), name='dense1'),
        BatchNormalization(name='bn_dense1'),
        Dropout(0.5, name='dropout_dense1'),

        # Output layer
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', name='predictions')
    ])

    return model

# Creating the complex CNN model
print("COMPLEX CNN - 5 CONVOLUTIONAL BLOCKS")
print("="*60)
complex_cnn = create_complex_cnn(input_shape=(48, 48, 1), num_classes=4)
# Displaying model architecture
complex_cnn.summary()
print("\nComplex CNN model with 5 convolutional blocks created successfully!")

# Compiling the Complex CNN model

    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

print("Complex CNN model compiled successfully!")

# Training parameters
EPOCHS = 30  # More epochs for complex model
print(f"\nStarting training of Complex CNN Model...")
print("="*60)

# Defining callbacks for better training
callbacks = [
    tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        'best_complex_cnn.h5',
        monitor='val_accuracy',
        save_best_only=True,
        save_weights_only=False,
        verbose=1
    ),
    tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_accuracy',
        patience=10,  # More patience for complex model
        restore_best_weights=True,
        verbose=1
    ),
    tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,
        patience=5,
        min_lr=1e-8,
        verbose=1
    )
]

# Training the Complex CNN model
history_complex = complex_cnn.fit(
    train_ds_gray_complex,
    validation_data=validation_ds_gray_complex,
    epochs=EPOCHS,
    callbacks=callbacks,
    verbose=1
)

  • (B)Provide the final proposed model specifications

  • Type: Sequential CNN with 5 convolutional blocks

  • Input Shape: 48481 (grayscale images)

  • Output Classes: 4 (for facial expressions: happy, sad, excited, neutral)

  • Total Blocks: 5 convolutional blocks + 1 dense head

  • Each block follows the pattern: Conv2D BatchNorm Conv2D BatchNorm MaxPooling Dropout

  • Dense Head

  • Global Average Pooling: Reduces 11256 to 256 features

  • Dense Layer: 256 neurons with ReLU activation

  • Batch Normalization + Dropout: 0.5 dropout rate

  • Output Layer: 4 neurons with softmax activation

  • Regularization Techniques

  • L2 Weight Decay: 1e-4 (0.0001) applied to all Conv2D and Dense layers

  • Batch Normalization: After every convolutional and dense layer

  • Dropout: Progressive increase from 0.25 to 0.5 across blocks

  • Global Average Pooling: Replaces flatten to reduce overfitting

Problem and solution summary

  • (A) Summary of the problem

  • we are given a dataset of human face immages with 4 expression happy, sad, surprised and neytral, we have to use DeepLearning andArtificial Intelligence techniques to create a computer vision model that can accurately detect these facial emotions

  • (B)Explain the reason for the proposed solution design

  • The proposed solution design was used for the following reasons :

  • 1.Hierarchical Feature Learning for Facial Expressions

  • The 5-block progressive architecture (3264128192256 filters) perfectly aligns with how facial emotions are structured:

  • Early blocks will capture basic facial features (edges, textures, facial contours)

  • Deeper blocks will learn complex emotion-specific patterns (smile curves, frown lines, eye crinkles)- Middle blocks detect facial components (eyes, mouth, eyebrows) -2. we are optimizung input size for bet results

  • The 48481 input shape is specifically chosen for facial emotion recognition:

  • Grayscale processing will focus on facial structure rather than skin color variations

  • and it will be computationally efficient while preserving essential facial details -3. we are using a Multi-Layer Regularization Strategy

  • Given that facial emotion datasets are typically small and prone to overfitting, this model has:

  • L2 regularization (1e-4) on all trainable layers

  • Progressive dropout (0.250.50) - increases with network depth

  • Batch normalization after every layer for stable training

  • Global Average Pooling instead of flatten to reduce parameters dramatically

    1. we are using preprocessing methods so as to provide seamless real world integration

  • The model has Built-in rescaling (1/255) handles raw image inputs directly

  • The Standardized input format used is compatible with webcam/image capture systems

  • Efficient inference suitable for real-time emotion detection applications
